@node Executable path
@section Executable path

@vindex mullvad-executable
The user option @code{mullvad-executable} specifies the path to the @samp{mullvad} command-line tool. It defaults to the result of @code{executable-find} at load time, which means it will be set automatically if @samp{mullvad} is on your @code{exec-path}.

If the executable is installed in a non-standard location, or if @code{executable-find} fails to locate it (in which case the default is an empty string), you should set this option manually:

@lisp
(setq mullvad-executable "/usr/local/bin/mullvad")
@end lisp

Every command validates this path before use. If the file does not exist or is not executable, an error is signaled immediately rather than producing a confusing shell error downstream.

@node Server mappings
@section Server mappings

@vindex mullvad-cities-and-servers
@vindex mullvad-websites-and-cities
The core of the package's routing logic lives in two association lists.

The user option @code{mullvad-cities-and-servers} maps human-readable city names to Mullvad server identifiers. Each entry is a cons cell of two strings. The default value is an empty list; you must populate it for the connect commands to work. For example:

@lisp
(setq mullvad-cities-and-servers
      '(("London" . "gb-lon-wg-001")
        ("Madrid" . "es-mad-wg-101")
        ("New York" . "us-nyc-wg-301")
        ("Sao Paulo" . "br-sao-wg-202")))
@end lisp

To discover the available server identifiers, use @samp{M-x mullvad-list-servers} (@ref{Listing servers}).

The user option @code{mullvad-websites-and-cities} adds a second level of indirection, mapping website names to the city names defined in @code{mullvad-cities-and-servers}. This is useful when you regularly access geo-restricted services and want to select them by name rather than remembering which city to use:

@lisp
(setq mullvad-websites-and-cities
      '(("Criterion Channel" . "New York")
        ("Library Genesis" . "London")
        ("HathiTrust" . "New York")))
@end lisp

When you connect via a website name, the package looks up the corresponding city in @code{mullvad-websites-and-cities}, then resolves that city to a server through @code{mullvad-cities-and-servers}.

@node Connection durations
@section Connection durations

@vindex mullvad-durations
The user option @code{mullvad-durations} controls the list of predefined duration choices (in minutes) presented when the user is prompted for a connection duration. The default value is @code{nil}, which means no predefined choices are offered and the user must type a duration manually each time.

When set to a list of integers, these values appear as completion candidates:

@lisp
(setq mullvad-durations '(1 5 10 30 60 120))
@end lisp

The user can still type a custom duration not in the list. Leaving the prompt blank (pressing @samp{RET} without input) means the connection will persist indefinitely until manually disconnected.

This option affects all commands that prompt for a duration, including @code{mullvad-connect-to-city} and @code{mullvad-connect-to-website} when called interactively (@ref{Connecting}).

@node Silent mode
@section Silent mode

@vindex mullvad-silent
The user option @code{mullvad-silent} controls whether the package emits status messages after connecting or disconnecting. The default value is @code{nil}, meaning messages are displayed in the echo area.

Set it to @code{t} to suppress all status messages:

@lisp
(setq mullvad-silent t)
@end lisp

This is particularly useful for programmatic usage, where you call connection functions from Lisp code and do not want messages cluttering the echo area. Note that individual commands also accept a SILENTLY argument, which provides per-call control without changing the global setting.

