@node Connection state
@section Connection state

@findex mullvad-is-connected-p
@findex mullvad-ensure-connected
@findex mullvad-ensure-disconnected
The function @code{mullvad-is-connected-p} returns @code{t} if the VPN is currently connected and @code{nil} otherwise. It works by invoking the @samp{mullvad status} command and checking the output for the word ``Connected''.

The functions @code{mullvad-ensure-connected} and @code{mullvad-ensure-disconnected} poll the connection state in a loop, waiting up to two seconds for the VPN to reach the expected state. They are called internally after connect and disconnect operations to ensure the command has taken effect before proceeding. This is necessary because the Mullvad CLI returns immediately while the connection is still being established.

@node Command execution
@section Command execution

@findex mullvad-run-command
@findex mullvad-shell-command
The function @code{mullvad-run-command} is the low-level interface for invoking the Mullvad CLI@. It accepts any number of string arguments, shell-quotes each one, and executes the resulting command. All arguments are passed through @code{shell-quote-argument} to prevent command injection.

The function @code{mullvad-shell-command} wraps @code{mullvad-run-command} with error handling and optional message suppression. If the command output begins with ``Error'' or ``error:'', an Emacs error is signaled. If the SILENTLY argument is non-nil (or @code{mullvad-silent} is @code{t}), messages are suppressed during execution (@ref{Silent mode}).

@node Server resolution
@section Server resolution

@findex mullvad-get-server
The function @code{mullvad-get-server} resolves a city or website name to a server identifier. It accepts a CONNECTION argument (the symbol @code{city} or @code{website}) and an optional SELECTION string. If SELECTION is @code{nil}, it prompts interactively with @code{completing-read}, requiring a match against the configured alist.

If the selection does not appear in the corresponding association list, a @code{user-error} is signaled. This prevents the package from silently passing invalid server identifiers to the Mullvad CLI@.

@node Timer management
@section Timer management

@findex mullvad-set-timer
@findex mullvad-cancel-timers
@findex mullvad-get-time-until-disconnect
The package maintains at most one disconnect timer at a time, stored in the variable @code{mullvad-timer}.

The function @code{mullvad-set-timer} creates a new timer that will call @code{mullvad-disconnect} after the specified number of minutes.

The function @code{mullvad-cancel-timers} cancels the running timer, if any, and resets the variable to @code{nil}. It is called automatically by both @code{mullvad-disconnect} and @code{mullvad-disconnect-after} before setting a new timer.

The function @code{mullvad-get-time-until-disconnect} returns a human-readable string describing the remaining time (e.g., ``24 minutes, 30 seconds''), or @code{nil} if no timer is active. This is used by @code{mullvad-status} (@ref{Checking status}).

@node Transient menu
@chapter Transient menu

@findex mullvad
The package provides a @samp{transient} menu accessible via @samp{M-x mullvad}. It groups all interactive commands under descriptive headings:

@multitable {aaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
@headitem Key
@tab Command
@tab Description
@item @samp{c}
@tab @code{mullvad-connect-to-city}
@tab Connect by city
@item @samp{w}
@tab @code{mullvad-connect-to-website}
@tab Connect by website
@item @samp{n}
@tab @code{mullvad-disconnect}
@tab Disconnect now
@item @samp{l}
@tab @code{mullvad-disconnect-after}
@tab Set a timed disconnect
@item @samp{d}
@tab @code{mullvad-dwim}
@tab Toggle connection
@item @samp{s}
@tab @code{mullvad-status}
@tab Display current status
@item @samp{r}
@tab @code{mullvad-list-servers}
@tab List available servers
@end multitable

The transient menu is the recommended entry point for interactive use. You might bind it to a convenient key:

@lisp
(global-set-key (kbd "C-c v") #'mullvad)
@end lisp

@node Programmatic usage
@chapter Programmatic usage

The package is designed to be called from Lisp code as well as interactively. A common pattern is to wrap an operation that requires a specific VPN location in an @code{:around} advice:

@lisp
(defun my-set-mullvad-for-gemini (orig-fun &rest args)
  "Connect to a US server before calling ORIG-FUN with ARGS."
  (when (eq gptel-model 'gemini-pro)
    (require 'mullvad)
    (mullvad-connect-to-website "Gemini" 10 'silently))
  (apply orig-fun args))

(advice-add 'gptel-curl-get-response :around #'my-set-mullvad-for-gemini)
@end lisp

The key points for programmatic use are:

@itemize
@item
Pass explicit city/website and duration arguments to avoid interactive prompts.
@item
Pass a non-nil SILENTLY argument (or set @code{mullvad-silent} to @code{t}) to suppress echo area messages.
@item
The connect commands are idempotent: if you are already connected to the requested server, no reconnection occurs.
@end itemize

@node Troubleshooting
@chapter Troubleshooting

@menu
* ``Mullvad executable not found or is not executable''::
* ``No server configured for @dots{}''::
* Connection does not complete::
@end menu

@node ``Mullvad executable not found or is not executable''
@section ``Mullvad executable not found or is not executable''

This error means @code{mullvad-executable} does not point to a valid executable. Verify that the Mullvad CLI is installed and check the value of the variable:

@lisp
(message "%s" mullvad-executable)
@end lisp

If the path is empty or wrong, set it manually (@ref{Executable path}). On macOS, the CLI is typically installed at @samp{/usr/local/bin/mullvad}. On Linux, it is usually at @samp{/usr/bin/mullvad}.

@node ``No server configured for @dots{}''
@section ``No server configured for @dots{}''

This error means you selected a city or website that does not appear in the corresponding association list. Check @code{mullvad-cities-and-servers} or @code{mullvad-websites-and-cities} and ensure the selection matches an existing key (@ref{Server mappings}).

@node Connection does not complete
@section Connection does not complete

After issuing a connect command, the package polls the connection state for up to two seconds. If the connection has not been established by then, the package proceeds without error, but subsequent commands may behave unexpectedly. This can happen if the Mullvad daemon is not running or if the network is unusually slow. Verify that the daemon is running with @samp{mullvad status} in a terminal.

